title: The Storm Will Pass
body:
Steve Gregory thought he’d got his family’s life sorted out. But life is never that simple…

“I’m parched, dude, back in a minute!”

“Good job, guys,” I say, lifting my bass guitar over my head and unplugging the lead in order to put it back in its case. The small crowd of people who have gathered just in front of where we were…

Read more…

summary: With 112 Emmy Nominations, Netflix Officially Rules Television
title: With 112 Emmy Nominations, Netflix Officially Rules Television
body:
Today, it came to pass. Five times after the breakout of House of Cards, a decade or so into the epoch of “prestige television, ” and a season or two into the decline of Game of Thrones, Netflix is eventually the monarch of television. The streaming giant beat out HBO with 112 Emmy nominations, besting the cable network’s 108 and intent its 17 -year streak of getting “the worlds largest” Television Academy nods.

It feels like it happened rapidly, but it was also a very long time seeing. Every year since 2013, when Netflix gained entry into the ranks of prestige television by earning a now-meager-seeming 14 nominations for its original programming, the service’s ascent has been written on the wall. Year over time, it’s pumped more and more cash into new programming( reports indicate Netflix could plunge anywhere from$ 8 billion to $13 billion on content this year, space more than HBO ). As it’s said and done, Netflix has been able to cast a huge net, pulling in viewers with big-hearted, expensive appearances like The Crown, which earned 13 nominations today, and cult-y astound smashes like Stranger Things, which nabbed 12.( Other Netflix nominees included GLOW, Ozark, Queer Eye, Black Mirror, and Grace and Frankie .)
